1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:03,523
Starting with the Python implementation.

2
00:00:03,473 --> 00:00:11,131
Here's a APIGateway class in python that implements rate limiting to control request flow.

3
00:00:11,131 --> 00:00:15,263
The init method is where the action happens.

4
00:00:15,263 --> 00:00:24,157
First, we define our APIGateway class — this encapsulates all the complexity in one clean interface.

5
00:00:24,157 --> 00:00:31,421
Then we set up the counts map on our instance — for O of 1 constant time lookups.

6
00:00:31,421 --> 00:00:35,473
This is why hash maps are interview gold.

7
00:00:35,473 --> 00:00:41,000
Next, we define the route function that takes path and token.

8
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:45,118
After that, we check if our boundary condition.

9
00:00:45,118 --> 00:00:50,447
Then we call APIGateway and store the result in gw.

10
00:00:50,447 --> 00:01:00,921
Finally, we print gw.route('/orders', '') to verify our result — because the order matters for our algorithm to work correctly.

